Come for the Optimism, stay for the in-depth analyses of tech companies and=
 trends:
Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B,
Happy Friday and welcome to our 18th Weekly Dose of Optimism. Go Phils.=20
The Weekly Dose is brought to you by=E2=80=A6Secureframe [ https://substack=
=2Ecom/redirect/de007a6a-5bc8-449d-a191-fffa710f13d3?r=3D9p0gt ]
Answering RFPs and security questionnaires is critical to closing deals and=
 growing revenue. But the manual process can delay deals or stop them cold.=
 Secureframe helps you respond to both fast with machine learning so you ca=
n quickly build trust with customers, close more deals, and accelerate spee=
d to revenue. Click here [ https://substack.com/redirect/de007a6a-5bc8-449d=
-a191-fffa710f13d3?r=3D9p0gt ] to schedule a demo of AI-powered Secureframe=
 Questionnaires today.
(1) The Crypto Story [ https://substack.com/redirect/4a6f4b23-1f6b-4812-82d=
d-bf10e2ad7e10?r=3D9p0gt ]
Matt Levine [ https://substack.com/redirect/c81ce1a5-34e4-4a84-9eb6-d0ec3ec=
981b4?r=3D9p0gt ] for Bloomberg
Conversely, I didn=E2=80=99t sit down and write 40,000 words to tell you th=
at crypto is dumb and worthless and will now vanish without a trace. That w=
ould be an odd use of time. My goal here is not to convince you that crypto=
 is building the future and that if you don=E2=80=99t get on board you=E2=
=80=99ll stay poor. My goal is to convince you that crypto is interesting, =
that it has found some new things to say about some old problems, and that =
even when those things are wrong, they=E2=80=99re wrong in illuminating way=
s.
When Matt Levine writes, we read. After years of coverage, Levine collected=
 his thoughts on =E2=80=9CCrypto=E2=80=9D in this 40,000 word super-deep-di=
ve. Levine=E2=80=99s perspective is an important one: he=E2=80=99s neither =
a crypto shill or arrogant skeptic. He=E2=80=99s a finance nerd. He might b=
e the finance nerd. On crypto, he appreciates the value of trustless system=
s, calls-out bad behavior and naked speculation, and thinks that whatever i=
s happening =E2=80=94 good or bad=E2=80=94is important, or at least illumin=
ating, for the broader financial ecosystem.
We won=E2=80=99t attempt to summarize the essay here =E2=80=94 it=E2=80=99s=
 40,000 words and Levine covers a bunch of different topics =E2=80=94 but i=
f you have a couple hours over the weekend, we recommend you take the time =
to read it. Or you can listen to Levine explain the story (and why he wrote=
 it) in this interview with Vox=E2=80=99s Peter Kafka [ https://substack.co=
m/redirect/8214448d-4b83-4888-966f-fe3decaf43b8?r=3D9p0gt ].
Levine=E2=80=99s whole piece, culminating in this final image, is a great e=
xpression of the brand of optimism we strive for: deep research, a lot of w=
ords, a recognition of the challenges, and a belief that it=E2=80=99s worth=
 trying to build better products and systems despite them.=20
(2) World Energy Outlook 2022 [ https://substack.com/redirect/8a962232-a210=
-4b70-a97a-9a53b6ee7b52?r=3D9p0gt ]
From The International Energy Agency
For the first time, a WEO scenario based on prevailing policy settings has =
global demand for each of the fossil fuels exhibiting a peak or plateau. In=
 the STEPS, coal use falls back within the next few years, natural gas dema=
nd reaches a plateau by the end of the decade, and rising sales of electric=
 vehicles (EVs) mean that oil demand levels off in the mid-2030s before ebb=
ing slightly to mid-century. Total demand for fossil fuels declines steadil=
y from the mid-2020s by around 2 exajoules per year on average to 2050, an =
annual reduction roughly equivalent to the lifetime output of a large oil f=
ield.
The IEA callin=E2=80=99 the top! This isn=E2=80=99t the first time people h=
ave called peak oil: I remember talking about near-term peak oil prediction=
s in my Energy & Economics class in college. But the numbers are compelling=
=2E=20
Despite a rise in fossil fuel usage this year, the IEA believes we are near=
 the peak of global fossil fuel usage and embarking on a long, slow, but ne=
cessary course towards a cleaner energy future. There=E2=80=99s much work t=
o be done, however. We do not currently have nearly the clean energy capaci=
ty to fully replace fossil fuel usage and we=E2=80=99ll likely need breakth=
rough innovations in some combination of nuclear, solar, wind, fusion, hydr=
ogen, and battery technologies to fully replace fossil fuels on the schedul=
e that we want to.=20
Thankfully, we are just a few desecrated masterpieces away from killing fos=
sil fuels. Potato mashing our way towards a cleaner future. (For the avoida=
nce of doubt: we=E2=80=99re kidding! These protests are unimaginably and em=
barrassingly dumb.)
(3) New data transmission record set using a single laser and a single opti=
cal chip [ https://substack.com/redirect/fe9bb208-de1c-465f-8c1f-8795c2702a=
2b?r=3D9p0gt ]
Lotte Krull for Phys.Org
h/t =E2=80=A6 Ashton Kutcher [ https://substack.com/redirect/1a00f30d-bc0b-=
43b0-bc76-57813b52827e?r=3D9p0gt ]?
In the experiment, the researchers succeeded in transmitting 1.8 Pbit/s, wh=
ich corresponds to twice the total global Internet traffic. And only carrie=
d by the light from one optical source. The light source is a custom-design=
ed optical chip, which can use the light from a single infrared laser [ htt=
ps://substack.com/redirect/12f14755-91ac-4a75-93e0-61b8045e0e76?r=3D9p0gt ]=
 to create a rainbow spectrum of many colors, i.e., many frequencies. Thus,=
 the one frequency (color) of a single laser can be multiplied into hundred=
s of frequencies (colors) in a single chip.
Kutch from way downtown!
A team of researchers achieved record-breaking data transmission speeds, mo=
ving more than 1.8 petabits per second using only a single laser and optica=
l chip. That=E2=80=99s a lot of data =E2=80=94 nearly 2x the daily global i=
nternet traffic. And the team is able to accomplish this using a single opt=
ical chip.
Without getting too much into the detail on the chip, this is an important =
breakthrough because one of these chips could replace 1,000s of lasers and =
when scaled, in aggregate, these chips could replace hundreds of thousands =
of lasers at internet hubs and data centers across the world. We=E2=80=99re=
 not there yet =E2=80=94 commercialization is still a few years out =E2=80=
=94 but this eventual swap could significantly reduce the climate footprint=
 of the internet.=20
(4) Time to Get Fit =E2=80=94 an Open Letter from Altimeter to Mark Zuckerb=
erg (and the Meta Board of Directors) [ https://substack.com/redirect/fc2e6=
17f-ecf7-4ea0-b209-af378f958fb3?r=3D9p0gt ]
Brad Gerstner [ https://substack.com/redirect/6b94b412-68a7-4ccd-b661-87503=
91d672d?r=3D9p0gt ] for Altimeter
We do not take job reductions lightly. These are not numbers on a spreadshe=
et. They are people with families and kids to support. With that said, we h=
ave a shortage of talent in Silicon Valley. Meta and other large companies =
have made it very difficult for start-ups to hire. We are confident that th=
ese employees will find replacement jobs and quickly be back to work on imp=
ortant inventions that will move us all forward.
Back in the early days of the pandemic, we wrote the first piece that fit t=
he =E2=80=9COptimism=E2=80=9D worldview that we hold today. Schumpeter=E2=
=80=99s Gale [ https://substack.com/redirect/c485edfd-64ea-436e-831f-7d6fea=
cfd8a7?r=3D9p0gt ] was Not Boring=E2=80=99s =E2=80=9Coptimistic view of une=
mployment." We wrote it in April 2020, as the first wave of pandemic-relate=
d layoffs pulsed through the tech world. Our argument at the time was three=
-fold:
Large-scale job loss from industry upheaval has happened many times before.=
=C2=A0So many times that it has an economics name, Creative Destruction, an=
d it has a badass name, Schumpeter=E2=80=99s Gale.
This was happening already, albeit more slowly and messily, as overfunded s=
tartups shifted from =E2=80=9Cgrowth at all costs=E2=80=9D to =E2=80=9Cprof=
itability at all costs.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0
This is going to unlock talent and be the best thing that could have happen=
ed to many of the people on those lists.
That could have been written today.=20
It seems inevitable now, with big misses from Alphabet and Meta, growing in=
vestor pressure, and rising interest rates, that there will be pretty massi=
ve layoffs across big tech over the coming months (although net job growth =
still may go up in the next year due to hiring.) People will lose their job=
s. Some will take a while to find new ones. That sucks, and we=E2=80=99re n=
ot trying to minimize it. But in the grand scheme of things, these layoffs =
will likely be a net positive for society and for those individuals.
Smart people will be unleashed on the next generation of important startups=
 that previously couldn=E2=80=99t afford to compete with the giants for top=
 talent. =E2=80=9CCuring cancer sounds great, but Meta is offering $600k in=
 total comp.=E2=80=9D And those people, despite periods of temporary uncert=
ainty, will land on their feet, working in places where they can make a big=
ger impact than they could inside of huge companies.=20
We=E2=80=99re looking forward to seeing the magic that happens when many of=
 the =E2=80=9Cbest minds of our generation=E2=80=9D are no longer =E2=80=9C=
thinking about how to make people click ads.=E2=80=9D
(5) Machine learning-powered drug discovery: Now and Tomorrow [ https://sub=
stack.com/redirect/00fbfdd4-eb8d-4b1e-90fc-e2d07e365a60?r=3D9p0gt ]
Ling Ning [ https://substack.com/redirect/59b02918-a0df-403e-afff-45342026e=
cc4?r=3D9p0gt ] for An Ounce of Biotechnology (h/t @JocelynnPearl [ https:/=
/substack.com/redirect/1db8474b-49ea-4a57-a7b5-4cce19ae65cc?r=3D9p0gt ])
In the drug discovery industry, AI-first companies are built around AI/ML m=
odels that predict disease targets, drug properties, treatment responses, e=
tc. They typically have the in-house infrastructure and expertise to genera=
te large-scale biodata to train and validate their models. They are essenti=
ally bio and tech companies at the same time.
Not Boring=E2=80=99s own Elliot Hershberg [ https://substack.com/redirect/b=
bc3b56c-3ba4-4c3a-bf5d-c2d39e2ec4bc?r=3D9p0gt ] wrote the definitive piece =
on techbio in Techbio Taxonomy [ https://substack.com/redirect/7c584f05-c0f=
0-4525-afaa-d4f863e59ad8?r=3D9p0gt ]. This piece, by Valkyrie Fund=E2=80=99=
s Ling Ning [ https://substack.com/redirect/59b02918-a0df-403e-afff-4534202=
6ecc4?r=3D9p0gt ], goes deep on one specific facet of the techbio movement:=
 machine learning in drug discovery. Ning, using slightly different termino=
logy from Elliot, describes the three main characteristics of AI-first biot=
echs:
Platform-first company structure
Versatile business models
Scaling up like tech companies
If you enjoy reading about major technological breakthroughs, science or ho=
w characteristics of tech ultimately seep into other industries, this is a =
strong read and we=E2=80=99d recommend subscribing to Elliot=E2=80=99s news=
letter Century of Biology [ https://substack.com/redirect/57ecc88b-32a7-4ef=
3-beb9-f6fc819fe593?r=3D9p0gt ] for weekly updates and analysis. The lines =
between biology company and technology company continue to blur, and we =E2=
=80=94 as humans =E2=80=94 are better off for it.
Bonus: bleeding edge ai [ https://substack.com/redirect/db228460-5bf9-4c07-=
8906-b1ecf0b519b8?r=3D9p0gt ]
Solo capitalist Lachy Groom [ https://substack.com/redirect/4f6ff3ea-5213-4=
ed0-a768-14f7e371c408?r=3D9p0gt ] launched a new project this week, bleedin=
g edge ai, which keeps a running list of the latest developments in AI.=20
The cool thing about bleeding edge is that it=E2=80=99s one big list, with =
links, that=E2=80=99s updated every time something new drops, making it a p=
erfect bookmark to keep coming back to to see all of the progress humans ar=
e making in AI in real-time. The latest one is a demo from Daniel Gross [ h=
ttps://substack.com/redirect/9cbae51c-0b43-4f27-863d-5b2d6afe15a9?r=3D9p0gt=
 ] for Videobook, which lets you =E2=80=9Cwatch=E2=80=9D audiobooks:
One step closer to the Enchanted Notebook=E2=80=A6=20
That=E2=80=99s all for this week. If you enjoyed this week=E2=80=99s email,=
 please share it with a friend or two!
We=E2=80=99ll be back in your inbox 9am EST on Monday morning. Enjoy the we=
ekend.
Packy

